Chipotle Reports First Quarterly Results Since Food Scare

   February 2, 2016 11:03 AM
   Filed Under: [68]CDC, [69]Centers for Disease Control and Prevention,
   [70]Chipotle, [71]Chipotle Mexican Grill Inc., [72]E. coli
   (credit: MANDEL NGAN/AFP/Getty Images)
   (credit: MANDEL NGAN/AFP/Getty Images)

   NEW YORK (AP) — Chipotle is likely to report its first quarterly
   decline in sales in at least a decade Tuesday after an E. coli outbreak
   linked to its restaurants sickened dozens of customers and damaged its
   reputation as a reliable place to get a fresh food.

   The Denver company warned last month that it believes sales fell 14.6
   percent at established locations. It would be the first drop-off since
   it went public in 2006, a dramatic turn for a chain whose explosive
   growth is partially due to its success in positioning itself as a
   superior alternative to fast food.

   The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention said this week that the
   outbreak appeared to be over and Chipotle Mexican Grill Inc., which has
   more than 1,900 locations, is about to launch a campaign to win back
   customers.

   In coming weeks, Chipotle will step up advertising and roll out deals
   to revive its sales and restore its reputation.

   It’s not clear how long that will take. In December, sales fell as much
   as 37 percent.

   Chipotle has also already disclosed that it expects profit for its
   fourth quarter to be between $1.70 and $1.90 per share. The results
   include a number of unusual charges, including costs to replace
   potentially contaminated food in restaurants, lab analysis of food
   samples, the hiring of a food safety consultant, and preliminary
   estimates for legal claims.

   The company has also been served with a federal subpoena tied to an
   investigation of a separate norovirus outbreak over the summer in
   California.

   Whether or not all of Chipotle’s customers will let bygones be bygones
   remains to be seen, but Wall Street appears ready to make up.

   While shares have fallen 23 percent since word of the outbreak spread,
   shares have turned positive for the year, though just barely.

   That’s still a lot better than the Standard & Poor’s index, which has
   fallen almost 7 percent in 2016.

   (© Copyright 2016 The Associated Press. All Rights Reserved. This
   material may not be published, broadcast, rewritten or redistributed.)
